	<h2 id="overview" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Overview</h2>
	<p>
		Graceful Degradation is a design approach that ensures systems continue to function even when parts fail or are not supported by the user’s environment.
	</p>
	<p>
		Instead of breaking completely, applications reduce non-essential features while preserving core functionality such as content access and navigation. This ensures usability across slow networks, older browsers, low-powered devices, or partial system failures.
	</p>
	<p>
		Originating from fault-tolerant system design, Graceful Degradation is widely used in web and distributed systems to maintain reliability and user trust. In web development, it typically means building for modern environments first, while still supporting older or constrained ones with a reduced but functional experience.
	</p>
	<h3>Key Idea In LRO Context</h3>
	<figure class="vf-figure vf-figure--align vf-figure--align-centered">
		<img src="{{ '/images/content_images/LRO diagram 2.3.a.avif' | url }}" alt="Aaron Walter's hierarchy of user needs" loading="lazy">
		<figcaption class="vf-figure__caption"></figcaption>
	</figure>
	<p>Within the Low Resource Optimisation (LRO) framework, Graceful Degradation ensures applications remain usable in constrained environments such as:</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Slow or unstable networks</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Low-end devices</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Older browsers</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Disabled or failing JavaScript/assets</li>
	</ul>
	<p>Core functionality is always preserved, even if advanced features fail.
Examples include:</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Text loads when images fail</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Cached data appears when APIs fail</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Basic forms work without JavaScript</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Simple layouts replace advanced CSS</li>
	</ul>

	<h2 id="why-lro" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Why this matters for LRO</h2>
	<p>
		Graceful Degradation improves access for users in real-world constrained conditions.
	</p>
	<p>Constraints include:</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Slow networks</strong> → API timeouts or failed asset loads</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Low-end devices</strong> → limited CPU/memory</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Limited data plans</strong> → limited support for modern CSS or JavaScript APIs</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Unstable connections</strong> → limited hardware capabilities and disabled JS or cookies</li>
	</ul>
	<p>
		Impact if ignored:
	</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Blank screens during load failures</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Broken workflows due to script errors</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Missing or inaccessible content due to unsupported technologies</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Complete application failure from minor issues</li>
	</ul>
	<p>Graceful Degradation prevents this by ensuring the system fails <strong>in pieces rather than all at once.</strong></p>

	<h2 id="key-principles" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Common problems</h2>
	<h3>Typical issues seen</h3>
	<p>Modern web systems are complex and depend on many interconnected components.</p>
	<p>Common issues that trigger degraded states include:</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>API Timeouts:</strong> Core information must always be accessible</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Network Failures:</strong> Enhancements should build on a reliable base</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Browser Compatibility Issues:</strong> Unsupported CSS features or JavaScript APIs</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Heavy Resource Requirements:</strong> Large frameworks overwhelming low-end devices</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Third-Party Dependency Failures:</strong> Analytics services or payment gateways becoming unavailable</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Server Overload:</strong> High traffic exceeding system capacity</li>
	</ul>

	<h2 id="implementation" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Implementation guidance</h2>
	<p>Use an HTML-first architecture with progressive CSS and JavaScript enhancement. Essential content should always be available before styling or interactivity loads.</p>
	<h3>HTML</h3>
	<p>
		Start with server-rendered HTML that contains the page’s core content and functionality. HTML loads quickly, requires little processing, and works across all browsers, making it the most reliable foundation in low-resource environments.
	</p>
	<p>Ensure that:</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Key content exists directly in the HTML</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Navigation links and forms work without JavaScript</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Semantic, accessible elements are used</li>
	</ul>
	<p>Avoid:</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Rendering content only through JavaScript</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Empty &lt;div id="root"&gt; pages</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Missing semantic markup</li>
	</ul>
	<pre class="vf-code-example__pre"><code>
&lt;main&gt;
&lt;h1&gt;Training Summary&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This content loads instantly without JavaScript.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/main&gt;
	</code></pre>
	<p>
		This form remains functional even if JavaScript does not load.
	</p>

	<h3>CSS</h3>
	<p>
		Use CSS to enhance layout and appearance, not to provide core functionality. Content should remain accessible even if CSS fails to load.
	</p>
	<p>Use:</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Modern CSS features progressively</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Simple fallbacks for older browsers</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Lightweight styling systems</li>
	</ul>
	<p>Avoid:</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Layouts that depend entirely on large CSS frameworks</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Heavy CSS resets</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Browser-specific hacks</li>
	</ul>
	<p>Fallback example:</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Modern browser → grid layout</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Older browser → simple stacked layout</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>JavaScript</h3>
	<p>
		Add JavaScript only once the core page is already working. Interactivity should enhance the experience, not be required for the page to function.
	</p>
	<p>
		JavaScript can fail due to disabled scripts, slow downloads, parsing errors, or browser incompatibility, so users must still be able to access essential core content and actions.
	</p>
	<p>Ensure that:</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Functionality works without JavaScript</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Feature detection is used before advanced behaviour runs</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Scripts load after the main content</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Heavy features are loaded only when needed</li>
	</ul>
	<p>Avoid:</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Rendering the entire site in JavaScript</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Large dependency chains</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Unhandled errors that break the page</li>
	</ul>
	<p>Example:</p>
	<pre class="vf-code-example__pre"><code>
&lt;button id="submit"&gt;Submit&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;script&gt;
		if ('fetch' in window) {
			// Enhanced behaviour
		}
&lt;/script&gt;
	</code></pre>
	<p>Build-time improvements:</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Reduce JavaScript bundle size</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Remove unnecessary dependencies</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Use modern CSS features progressively</li>
	</ul>
	<p>Runtime behaviour:</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Load enhancements after essential content</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Conditionally load advanced features</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Use feature detection before execution</li>
	</ul>
	<p>Fallback strategies</p>
	<p>Provide simple alternatives for advanced features, for example:</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">System fonts before web fonts</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Standard forms before AJAX forms</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Basic layouts before CSS Grid layouts</li>
	</ul>
	<p>Key guidance</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Never block content behind JavaScript</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Always deliver essential content through HTML</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Load enhancements only when supported and needed</li>
	</ul>
	<p>Use this approach when building public websites, supporting a wide range of devices, targeting global audiences, or meeting accessibility requirements.</p>
	<p>Basic example</p>
	<p>Minimal progressive enhancement pattern.</p>
	<pre class="vf-code-example__pre"><code>
&lt;main&gt;
&lt;h1&gt;Latest Updates&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Content loads immediately.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/main&gt;
&lt;script defer src="enhancements.js"&lt;&lt;/script&lt;
	</code></pre>
	<p>This ensures the content loads first, while enhancements load later.</p>
	<p>Advanced example</p>
	<p>Feature detection example.</p>
	<pre class="vf-code-example__pre"><code>
&lt;main&gt;
&lt;h1&gt;Latest Updates&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Content loads immediately.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/main&gt;
&lt;script defer src="enhancements.js"&lt;&lt;/script&lt;
	</code></pre>
	<p>Enhanced functionality is only enabled if supported.</p>

	<h2 id="dos-donts" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Do / Don't</h2>

	<h4>Do</h4>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Deliver core content via HTML</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Ensure functionality works without JavaScript</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Load enhancements progressively</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Use feature detection</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Test under slow network conditions</li>
	</ul>

	<h4>Don't</h4>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Depend entirely on client-side rendering</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Ship large JavaScript bundles unnecessarily</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Hide content while assets load</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Assume browsers are modern</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Break functionality when scripts fail</li>
	</ul>

	<h2 id="checklist" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Checklist</h2>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Core content loads without JavaScript</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Works on slow network profiles</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Page weight minimised</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Essential tasks work without enhancements</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Failure scenarios handled gracefully</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Tested with CSS and JavaScript disabled</li>
	</ul>

	<h2 id="metrics-tools" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Metrics & Tools</h2>
	<p>These metrics are used to evaluate performance and resilience in low-resource environments:</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Page Weight -</strong> Total size of HTML, CSS, JavaScript, images, and other assets loaded for the initial view.</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>First Contentful Paint (FCP) -</strong> Time until the first meaningful content appears on screen.</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Time to Interactive (TTI) -</strong> Time until the page becomes fully interactive and responsive to user input.</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>JavaScript Execution Time -</strong> Time spent parsing and executing JavaScript, especially during initial load.</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Script Error Rate -</strong> Frequency of runtime errors that impact functionality or user experience.</li>
	</ul>

	<h2 id="benchmarks" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Benchmarks</h2>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Initial page weight: <strong>under 300 KB<</strong>/li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Core content visible: <strong>within 3 seconds on slow networks</strong></li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">JavaScript execution: <strong>kept minimal during initial load</strong></li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Interactive readiness: <strong>progressive, not blocked by scripts</strong></li>
	</ul>

	<h2 id="tools" class="vf-u-margin--0 vf-u-padding__top--400 vf-u-padding__bottom--600">Tools</h2>
	<p>These tools support measurement, simulation, and validation:</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Lighthouse - </strong>performance, accessibility, and best practice auditing</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>WebPageTest - </strong> real-world network and device simulation</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Chrome DevTools - </strong> performance profiling and debugging</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Network Throttling - </strong> simulation of slow/unstable connections</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Synthetic Testing Profiles - </strong> automated testing under controlled device/network conditions</li>
	</ul>

